{"parse":{"title":"Captain of the ship doctrine","pageid":40350038,"revid":846886990,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Captain of the ship doctrine</b> is the <a href=\"/wiki/Legal_doctrine\" title=\"Legal doctrine\">legal doctrine</a> which holds that, during an <a href=\"/wiki/Surgery\" title=\"Surgery\">operation</a> in an <a href=\"/wiki/Operating_room\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Operating room\">operating room</a>, a <a href=\"/wiki/Surgeon\" title=\"Surgeon\">surgeon of record</a> is liable for all actions conducted in the course of the operation.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> The doctrine is a form of the \"borrowed servant doctrine\", in which a party usually liable for his, her, its, or their actions is absolved of responsibility when that \"borrowed servant\" is asked to do something that is outside of the bounds of policy.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Captain_of_the_ship_doctrine&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The doctrine was coined in <i>McConnel v. Williams</i>, 361 Pa. 355, 65 A.2d 243, 246 (1949), in which the <a href=\"/wiki/Supreme_Court_of_Pennsylvania\" title=\"Supreme Court of Pennsylvania\">Supreme Court of Pennsylvania</a> ruled that, \"it can readily be understood that in the course of an operation in the operating room of a hospital, and until the surgeon leaves that room at the conclusion of the operation... he is in the same complete charge of those who are present and assisting him as in the captain of a ship over all on board, and that such supreme control is indeed essential in view of the high degree of protection to which an anesthetized, unconscious patient is entitled...\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The doctrine emerged in 1949 and was popular in the 1950s, but the application of this doctrine declined as patients who suffered a <a href=\"/wiki/Tort\" title=\"Tort\">tort</a> sued under the <a href=\"/wiki/Charitable_immunity\" title=\"Charitable immunity\">charitable immunity</a> doctrine.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Murphy_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Murphy-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In the 21st-century, consistent with the Supreme Courts of multiple states, the <a href=\"/wiki/Supreme_Court_of_Wisconsin\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Supreme Court of Wisconsin\">Supreme Court of Wisconsin</a> declined to adopt the doctrine.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Murphy_4-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Murphy-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> Although the doctrine has been deemed \"anachronistic\", a \"prostrate doctrine\" and \"indiscriminate repetition\", among other things, the phrase remains in current usage.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Murphy_4-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Murphy-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Captain_of_the_ship_doctrine&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Charitable_immunity\" title=\"Charitable immunity\">Charitable immunity</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Captain_of_the_ship_doctrine&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Blumenreich, Gene A. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.aana.com/newsandjournal/Documents/legal_briefs_0293_p003.pdf\">\"Captain of the Ship\"</a> <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(PDF)</span>. <i>Legal Briefs</i>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Legal+Briefs&amp;rft.atitle=Captain+of+the+Ship&amp;rft.aulast=Blumenreich&amp;rft.aufirst=Gene+A.&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.aana.com%2Fnewsandjournal%2FDocuments%2Flegal_briefs_0293_p003.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACaptain+of+the+ship+doctrine\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Scott, Edwin L. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://digitalcommons.law.villanova.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1538&amp;context=vlr\">\"Agency - Borrowed Servant Doctrine - Surgeon Is Responsible for the Pre-Operative Negligence ofAnesthetist\"</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Agency+-+Borrowed+Servant+Doctrine+-+Surgeon+Is+Responsible+for+the+Pre-Operative+Negligence+ofAnesthetist&amp;rft.aulast=Scott&amp;rft.aufirst=Edwin+L.&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fdigitalcommons.law.villanova.edu%2Fcgi%2Fviewcontent.cgi%3Farticle%3D1538%26context%3Dvlr&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACaptain+of+the+ship+doctrine\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Capule, Rodel V. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.pcp.org.ph/images/stories/pjim_49/issue2_apr-jun2011/0_IV-VLegal_Prescription.pdf\">\"A Surgeon Is Not Always the \"Captain of the Ship<span style=\"padding-right:0.2em;\">\"</span>\"</a> <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(PDF)</span>. <i>Philippine Journal of Internal Medicine</i>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Philippine+Journal+of+Internal+Medicine&amp;rft.atitle=A+Surgeon+Is+Not+Always+the+%22Captain+of+the+Ship%22&amp;rft.aulast=Capule&amp;rft.aufirst=Rodel+V.&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.pcp.org.ph%2Fimages%2Fstories%2Fpjim_49%2Fissue2_apr-jun2011%2F0_IV-VLegal_Prescription.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACaptain+of+the+ship+doctrine\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n